---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Kimchi Jjigae with Pork Belly" description="Kimchi Jjigae with Pork Belly — a quick, deeply flavoured Korean stew adapted for Singapore kitchens. Ready in 25 minutes.">

  <header class="article-header">
    <div class="article-pillar-tag"><a href="/cook/">Cook</a> &middot; Main</div>
    <h1>Kimchi Jjigae with Pork Belly</h1>
    <div class="article-byline">
      <span class="author">Eric Sim</span><span class="separator">/</span>
      <time datetime="2026-03-16">March 16, 2026</time><span class="separator">/</span>
      <span>5 min read</span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <figure class="article-featured-image">
    <div class="image-placeholder">[ featured: bubbling kimchi jjigae in earthenware pot ]</div>
    <figcaption>Kimchi jjigae served straight from the stove. The longer your kimchi has fermented, the deeper the flavour. Photo: Eric Sim / The Hansang</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <div class="article-video">
    <div class="article-video-inner">
      <div class="article-video-placeholder"><div class="article-video-play"></div><span>Watch on Instagram</span></div>
    </div>
    <p class="article-video-caption">Watch the full recipe on Instagram <a href="https://www.instagram.com/thehansang.sg">@thehansang.sg</a></p>
  </div>

  <div class="article-layout">
    <article class="article-content">

      <aside class="recipe-card" aria-label="Recipe overview">
        <div class="recipe-card-title">Recipe Card</div>
        <div class="recipe-card-grid">
          <div class="recipe-card-item"><span class="recipe-card-label">Servings</span><span class="recipe-card-value">2&ndash;3</span></div>
          <div class="recipe-card-item"><span class="recipe-card-label">Prep Time</span><span class="recipe-card-value">10 min</span></div>
          <div class="recipe-card-item"><span class="recipe-card-label">Cook Time</span><span class="recipe-card-value">15 min</span></div>
          <div class="recipe-card-item"><span class="recipe-card-label">Difficulty</span><span class="recipe-card-value">Easy</span></div>
        </div>
      </aside>

      <p>Kimchi jjigae is the dish every Korean household has on rotation. It is fast, forgiving, and almost impossible to mess up if your kimchi is sour enough. This version uses pork belly for richness and soft tofu to balance the heat.</p>

      <p>The key is aged kimchi. Fresh, crunchy kimchi will not give you the deep, funky sourness that makes this stew work. If your kimchi has been sitting in the fridge for three weeks or longer, you are in good shape.</p>

      <p>This recipe is written for a Singapore kitchen. No special equipment needed, just a regular pot and a stove.</p>

      <aside class="ingredient-list" aria-label="Ingredients">
        <div class="ingredient-list-title">Ingredients</div>
        <ul>
          <li><span class="ingredient-check" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" tabindex="0" aria-label="Mark ingredient as prepared"></span>200g pork belly, sliced</li>
          <li><span class="ingredient-check" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" tabindex="0" aria-label="Mark ingredient as prepared"></span>1 cup aged kimchi, roughly chopped</li>
          <li><span class="ingredient-check" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" tabindex="0" aria-label="Mark ingredient as prepared"></span>1 tbsp gochugaru</li>
          <li><span class="ingredient-check" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" tabindex="0" aria-label="Mark ingredient as prepared"></span>1 tbsp gochujang</li>
          <li><span class="ingredient-check" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" tabindex="0" aria-label="Mark ingredient as prepared"></span>1 tsp sugar</li>
          <li><span class="ingredient-check" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" tabindex="0" aria-label="Mark ingredient as prepared"></span>1 block soft tofu</li>
          <li><span class="ingredient-check" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" tabindex="0" aria-label="Mark ingredient as prepared"></span>2 cups water or anchovy stock</li>
          <li><span class="ingredient-check" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" tabindex="0" aria-label="Mark ingredient as prepared"></span>1 spring onion, sliced</li>
          <li><span class="ingredient-check" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" tabindex="0" aria-label="Mark ingredient as prepared"></span>1 tsp sesame oil</li>
        </ul>
      </aside>

      <aside class="sg-swap" aria-label="Singapore ingredient substitutions">
        <div class="sg-swap-title">Singapore Swap</div>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Aged kimchi:</strong> Any Korean mart on Tanjong Pagar or Don Don Donki house brand</li>
          <li><strong>Pork belly:</strong> Pre-sliced from FairPrice Finest or Donki</li>
          <li><strong>Anchovy stock:</strong> Instant dashida powder works in a pinch</li>
        </ul>
      </aside>

      <aside class="ad-inline" aria-label="Advertisement"><div class="ad-slot"><span class="ad-slot-label">Partner</span>Advertisement</div></aside>

      <h2>Instructions</h2>

      <div class="recipe-steps">
        <div class="recipe-step"><h3>Prep the pork and kimchi</h3><p>Slice the pork belly into bite-sized pieces. Roughly chop the kimchi, reserving the juice.</p></div>
        <div class="recipe-step"><h3>Saut&eacute;</h3><p>Heat sesame oil in a pot over medium-high. Cook pork belly until lightly browned, 2&ndash;3 minutes. Add kimchi and cook until softened.</p></div>
        <figure class="inline-photo"><div class="image-placeholder">[ photo: pork belly and kimchi saut&eacute;ing in pot ]</div><figcaption>Let the pork belly get some colour before adding the kimchi.</figcaption></figure>
        <div class="recipe-step"><h3>Season and simmer</h3><p>Add gochugaru, gochujang, sugar, and reserved kimchi juice. Pour in water or stock. Bring to a boil, then reduce to a simmer for 10 minutes.</p></div>
        <div class="recipe-step"><h3>Add tofu</h3><p>Slide in the soft tofu in large spoonfuls. Simmer 3 more minutes.</p></div>
        <div class="recipe-step"><h3>Serve</h3><p>Garnish with spring onion. Serve bubbling hot with steamed rice.</p></div>
      </div>

      <aside class="ad-inline" aria-label="Advertisement"><div class="ad-slot"><span class="ad-slot-label">Partner</span>Advertisement</div></aside>

      <section class="recipe-tips" aria-label="Cooking tips">
        <h2>Tips</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>The older your kimchi, the better this stew will taste. If your kimchi is less than two weeks old, add an extra splash of rice vinegar to fake the funk.</li>
          <li>Do not stir the tofu too aggressively. You want soft, pillowy chunks, not a broken-up mess.</li>
          <li>This reheats beautifully the next day. The flavours deepen overnight in the fridge.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

    </article>

    <aside class="ad-sidebar" aria-label="Advertisements">
      <div class="ad-sidebar-inner">
        <div class="ad-slot"><span class="ad-slot-label">Partner</span>Advertisement</div>
        <div class="ad-slot"><span class="ad-slot-label">Partner</span>Advertisement</div>
      </div>
    </aside>
  </div>

